Civil Rights Movement issues travel alert to Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) has issued warnings to people of color traveling to Missouri based on discriminatory state policies and racist attacks.
"The NAACP's travel advice to the state of Missouri, effective August 28, 2017, calls on African-American travelers, visitors, and residents of Missouri to heed heightened attention when traveling across the state as a result of a series of contentious racially motivated incidents currently occurring across the state," the association said in a statement.
The NAACP said the move was based on current Missouri state laws that make it difficult to defend racist-motivated acts in court, as well as the actions of law enforcement agencies that disproportionately target minorities.
“Civil rights are being violated.
People are stopped by police because of the color of their skin, they are attacked or killed," NAACP president Rod Chapel told the Kansas City Star.
“We have the highest number of complaints so far.”
This is the first warning of its kind issued to the U.S. state.
Among the incidents cited by the organization were racially motivated insults directed against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died in questionable circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas while traveling across the state and was thrown into custody without charges of committing a crime.
The travel advice also draws attention to a recent statement by the Missouri Attorney General's Office, which states that black drivers are 75% more likely to be stopped by the police.
“The purpose of a travel recommendation is to alert people and warn their families, friends and co-workers about what could happen in Missouri,” Chapel said.
"People need to be prepared - they should bring money to pay the bail or warn their relatives that they are going to travel in the state."
According to current FBI program numbers, there were 100 hate crimes reported in Missouri in 2015, placing the state at sixteenth place among all states.
The travel warning is also a response to the new Missouri law, which makes it difficult to sue the company for discrimination in providing accommodation or employment.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) has issued travel recommendations for Texas and Arizona after states passed an immigration law that allows state officials to detain people on charges of violating that law, which the ACLU says is designed to improve racial profiling.
Travel recommendations are usually issued by the State Department for Foreign Countries, but recently advocacy groups have resorted to these measures in response to specific laws and trends within the US.
