The current movement protesting Dutch rules quickly turned its anger against the Jakarta government, which controlled the entire region except for foreign journalists or civil rights supervisors.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua - independent Papua New Guinea occupied the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is a remote and ravaged city, which can be reached after a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire, and then a five-hour stomach cramping ride.
Mass transit does not work at this location.
The city with 19,000 inhabitants consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, roofs of wool sheets in shades of gray and rusty color.
Very few Indonesians, let alone journalists, have looked at this place, and virtually no foreigners.
Before the arrival of Christians, locals worshiped a god named Uga Tamee.
And that's not all.
“We weren’t used to wearing this dress,” Bardina says, pointing to her colorful, hand-knit turban, dark t-shirt, and bright skirt.
“We used to only carry leaves.”
Papua is Indonesia’s poorest province, with 28% of the population living below the poverty line, and child mortality and literacy among the worst in Asia.
It is also the country of gold.
The largest and most profitable gold mine in the world, Grasberg, owned by Freeport McMoran of American Phoeenix, is located just 60 miles from Paniai - a rocky province about the size of New Jersey, home to about 153,000 residents.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper here.
In addition, Papua supports an estimated $78 billion worth of logging.
However, these riches are a source of suffering for Papuans and a guarantee of oppression by the powerful Indonesian army.
An investigation conducted by the New York Times in 2005 found that Freeport paid local military officials and troops about $20 million between 1998 and 2004, including an amount of $150,000 for one officer.
Papuans calling for self-government threaten this golden goose and are therefore severely repressed.
According to human rights activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed since 1969, and thousands more have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military.
The mass murders in the Papuan tribal area during the 1970s were tantamount to genocide, the Asian Human Rights Commission said.
Last year alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region.
We Will Lose Everything, a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, describes the atrocities that occurred last year, such as extrajudicial executions, torture - according to another report, rape and electrocution are particularly popular - and the brutal repression of peaceful protesters.
“It’s difficult to count the number of victims because the incidents happen every week,” said Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
The whole situation was aggravated by the fact that Papuan resources are attracting colonists to Indonesia.
Of the province’s 3.5 million people, 83% are Christian, but the demographics are changing with the influx of Muslim immigrants from the Indonesian islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese canteens sell fried chicken and gado-gado, or a mixture of vegetables with peanut sauce.
Local people are struggling to survive.
“Immigrants started selling chicken and vegetables in traditional markets at lower prices than local Papuans,” explains Abeth You, 24, who was born in Paniai and moved to the provincial capital of Jayapura to work.
"The indigenous people of Papua - mom-mom (women) - have lost their jobs."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, nicknamed Jokowi, promised to address inequality and rights violations as part of his 2014 presidential campaign.
The former carpenter secured and made his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta 27 of the 29 districts of Papua, including Paniai.
But very little has changed in Papua, and the local people feel betrayed.
"Our hearts have been broken because in 2014 we voted for Jokpwi in the hope that he will hear our call for justice," You said.
In fact, just two months after Jakowi’s inauguration in October, Paniai was shocked.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were singing Christmas songs at a campfire in the town of Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on motorbikes emerged from the twilight of the night.
Two of the surprised children told them to turn on the lights.
One of the soldiers was touched by this rebuke and tone, and later returned with four other soldiers, local parish priest Yavedt Tebai said.
Two of the soldiers in a drunken state chased a group of children and beat them with the butts of their weapons, citing victims and witnesses of the events.
One of the soldiers then fired on a group of children.
One of the children, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
Hours later, someone set fire to a nearby electoral commission building, and the next day things escalated.
About 1,000 young Papuan men and women gathered on the football field in front of the local police station and army headquarters, demanding justice.
They came up with ceremonial hunting bows and performed a waita dance - in which a circle is run and the singing of birds is imitated - of the Papuan tribe Mee Pago.
Several Protestants began throwing stones at the buildings.
With escalating tension, the soldiers were ordered via radio: “If the crowd tries to resist at least three times, you are allowed to shoot,” the official document said, the content of which was never published in local media.
Yeremias Kayame (56), the head of Enarotali district Kego Koto, recognized the impending danger and urged residents to disperse to their homes.
But no one paid any attention to his words.
“When I turned around, someone shot me in the left wrist,” he told TIME on the porch of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame does not yet know who the shooter was, but according to him, the bullet belonged to one of the soldiers present.
“There were a lot of people around and a lot of shooting,” he added.
One of the locals, Alfius Youw, was hit three times, according to his cousin who witnessed the shooting.
“I ran to the body to make sure it was him,” Yohanes told TIME in a sullen voice, who, like many Indonesians, uses only one name.
“I saw that he was dead...I kissed him.”
The Papuan police inspector, General Yotje Mende, told reporters that his officers were merely “ensuring” the station that was under attack.
“We have to defend ourselves when people threaten us with death,” Pudjo Sulistiyo, a spokesman for the Papuan police, said in 2015.
“It’s a matter of life and death.”
According to Human Rights Watch, five protesters were killed and many escaped injury.
The news of the killings swept through the Jakarta media the following day.
Three weeks later, Jokowi gave a passionate speech in Jayapura, expressing his understanding for the victims' families and promising to address the violence in Papua.
"I demand an immediate solution to this problem so that it can never be repeated," he said.
National Security Minister Wiranto announced in October 2016 that he would introduce an extrajudicial mechanism to resolve past acts of violence.
Almost immediately, however, excuses began to be made.
“Most of the violent acts took place a long time ago.
Some of these occurred in the 1990s and some at the beginning of the 21st century.
I mean, we are committed to punishing these acts of violence, but it will not be an easy task," he said.
However, in an interview on June 5 for the TIME weekly held in Jakarta, Wiranto claimed that he did not plan to introduce any measures in Papua.
Instead, he said, “all cases will be brought before the court.”
Wiranto, who was accused by the UN of "crimes against humanity" on the basis of more than 1,000 deaths during the independent 1999 elections in East Timor, said 11 human rights violations in Papua had been settled so far, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the victims of the Paniai shooting welcomed his claims with disbelief.
“I’ve been interviewed four times in the last three years, but I haven’t seen anything yet,” Yohanes said.
"I'm tired."
As he says, he still lives in fear a few years later.
“I’m scared,” he says.
"I'm afraid the army will arrest me or someone will shoot me."
His brother Yacobus confirmed the view of many Paniai residents who are afraid to talk about the incident.
According to him, he was beaten by members of the army after helping to bury four of the victims.
“After the bodies were buried, the army started looking for me,” he said.
And the shooting hasn't stopped yet.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired on villagers in neighboring Deiyai.
The skirmish, in which one person died and another 17 were injured, occurred between the villagers and the manager of the construction company, who refused to provide assistance in transporting the unconscious man to the hospital.
Ravianus Douw, 24, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died en route to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested outside the company building.
According to police, the villagers threw stones at the members and the response was a warning shot.
However, locals say a mobile brigade (Indonesian paramilitaries police) began shooting into the crowd, killing one person.
“There was panic, we were afraid of retaliation,” said Domingga Badii, 29, who lives near the hospital and witnessed the arrival of the injured.
“I didn’t leave the house for two days.”
The Deiyai parliament demanded the punishment of the participating police officers and the withdrawal of the mobile brigade from the area.
Paniai has always been a thorn in the side of the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development only deepens the separation of the indigenous Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal peoples who live in the central highlands.
Many of them joined the Liberation Movement of Papua (OPM) - an army of insurgents that protects the rights of Papuans by attacking and abducting Indonesian police officers.
Some of the leaders of the OPM come from Paniai. These include Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
As a result of the attacks, the military has in recent years arrested and arbitrarily detained thousands of Paniai residents, all under the guise of "ensuring national sovereignty".
Some of them will never be seen again.
Paniai is known among the people of Papua as a "tragic and forgotten place".
The fire is fueled by poverty.
The little rice that is sold in Enarotali is too expensive for the locals.
And bread is equally unattainable.
The locals grow their food: mainly sweet potatoes, fruits and leafy vegetables.
Women work in the fields; each of them cultivates four or five fields with sweet potatoes.
Most of the harvest is intended for the needs of the family, the rest are sold at the local market.
Ten pieces of sweet potatoes cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Since Nabire Airport opened more air routes and new immigrants began flowing into the country, there has been an increase in economic inequality between native Papuans and immigrants.
Already so few jobs are usually filled by more educated and wealthy immigrants.
Papuans rarely have the capital and education they need to get into business.
“Young people are moving out of villages because of lack of jobs and money,” said John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai tribal council.
Thanks to isolation, the province of Papua is hidden from the world.
Strict rules for foreign journalists also contribute to this.
Earlier this year, two French journalists, Franck Escudie and Basile Longchamp, were expelled from the papaya for "lack of cooperation with the authorities", despite the fact that they were given such a rare permit to film.
Phelim Kine, deputy director of the Asian branch of Human Rights Watch, promised in his election campaign to abolish strict rules for journalists and achieve transparency and development, but this never happened.
“Foreign journalists working in the rebellious easternmost areas of Papua and West Papua are at great risk: non-recognition of visas and blacklisting,” he said in a statement.
The lack of news from the pens of foreign journalists means that international pressure on Indonesians in the case of Papua is largely limited.
In March, six Pacific nations - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands - urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "various and widespread acts of violence" in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
These countries have also supported OPM in the past.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir slammed the allegations, telling reporters in Jakarta that "In Indonesia, the democratic system is still in place and the media is free, so it is difficult to disguise evidence of human rights violations."
Local people are calling for the participation of foreign governments.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, headed by human rights envoy Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapurau on May 4, local people called out, according to a source who also attended the meeting but wanted to remain anonymous, the slogan "we want freedom".
Another election is scheduled for 2019, but Papuans say they will not vote for Jokowi.
"Jokowi is a person who has good intentions but is surrounded by people associated with the Paniai shooting," said Gobau, chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokowi to know that the inhabitants of Paniai - in addition to living in constant fear of a robber army - are wallowing in poverty, poor education, and a health system.
Gobai claims that the inhabitants of Paniai, like other Papuans, consider their vote to be a "debt" that must be repaid to Jokowi.
“They don’t want money, they want justice,” he said.
Despite threats and intimidation from the family of the victims of the Pan-Ai shooting, they continue their last symbolic act of defiance: burying the bodies of the victims on the property opposite the police and army station.
Knowing that justice will never be done enough, at least he will not allow those responsible to forget their crimes.
“A member of our family was killed,” Yacobus said with his head down.
“What can we do?”
