This is the second time The Torch has burned in Dubai.
One of the world’s largest residential skyscrapers caught fire in Dubai on Friday, with firefighters having to evacuate all residents 337 meters tall and 79 storey buildings.
In the last two years, this is the second fire of this high-rise building, which bears the convenient name The Torch.
All residents of the building were evacuated and there were no injuries. The cause of the fire is unknown.
“We were asleep and the alarm woke us up. We heard screaming.
It took us ten minutes to get down from the 50th floor," said Geroge, one of the occupants of the skyscraper.
Dubai Civil Defense said firefighters managed to get the fire under control around 4am (00:00 GMT) before continuing to cool the building.
Government officials added that they provide replacement accommodation for affected residents.
The incident could spark a renewed debate over the safety of the materials used to line high-rise buildings around the world.
The results of the investigation launched by Torch after the fire in 2015 showed that the lining and external panels used for decoration or insulation were the most damaged.
British police said the insulation and cladding system at London's Grenfell Tower may have contributed to the rapid spread of the fire in June, which killed nearly 80 people.
