EPA Chief Scott Pruitt on Postponing Planned Directives to Reduce Obama Administration Emissions
After the Environmental Protection Agency was sued by fifteen states, its head Scott Pruitt rescinded his earlier decision to delay implementation of the former Obama administration's plan to reduce carbon dioxide emissions.
Pruitt has introduced changes to his plan, making it more responsive than previous governments to the needs of state environmental regulators.
However, he did not mention a legal challenge filed against his previous position in the federal appeals court.
This includes the latest deadline, set for October 1, for countries to comply with the 2015 regulation to reduce ground-level ozone.
Pruitt announced in June that he would postpone the deal for one year and order a more detailed study of the plan to avoid “interventions with local decisions or threatened economic growth.”
Pruitt, who served as Oklahoma’s state attorney general before being appointed by President Donald Trump, has long served as a staunch opponent of tougher environmental regulations.
Since settling in Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly moved or delayed the regulations proposed by the chemical and fossil industries.
Wednesday's sudden turnaround is the biggest legal setback for Pruitt's regulatory agenda.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA executor exceeded its authority in an effort to delay the Obama administration's plan to require oil and gas companies to reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released on Wednesday evening, Pruitt proposed his version of the ozone standards and strengthened the EPA's commitment to working with states through comprehensive processes and meeting new standards within a given timeframe.
“Under the previous administration, the EPA often missed deadlines and waited to be sued by activist groups and others, agreeing to settle and further set plans,” Pruitt said, filing more than a dozen lawsuits with the EPA in his previous position.
“We do not believe in regulation through litigation and we take the deadline seriously.
We never joke about our status and the authority that comes from it."
However, the EPA's statement states that Pruitt may at some point use "the possibility of a delay and any other legally available authority" to ensure that regulations "will be based on sound policy and the most accessible information".
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a more comprehensive rewrite of the ozone rules.
The White House budget passed last month seeks to defer implementation of the 2015 rules for at least eight years.
The measure still did not pass the Senate.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who headed the coalition of states that sued the EPA this week, said the group would not allow legal pressure.
“The turnaround in the EPA’s views - following our lawsuit - is an important victory for the health and safety of those 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans directly affected by air pollution,” Schneiderman added.
New York was joined by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Washington, and Washington, D.C.
Ground-level ozone is formed when common harmful substances emitted by automobiles, power plants, oil refineries, chemical power plants, and other sources react in the atmosphere with sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause serious respiratory problems in sensitive people and thousands of premature deaths each year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists acknowledge Pruitt's sudden change with gratitude.
“It’s worrying what pressure needs to be put to change the minds of those responsible and to protect the air we breathe,” said Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biological Diversity.
“We must continue to struggle with the Trump administration’s ideological drive to help polluters and special interests.”
He spilled acid on the man, yet he's not dangerous, according to the court.
You never know what might happen to you.
One minute you're home with your family and you're laughing, the next minute your whole life changes from the ground up.
And worst of all, there's nothing you can do about it.
A similar fate met Andreas Christopheros from Great Britain, whose face was glued with acid by an unknown assailant, who was eventually acquitted.
This was reported by Reuters website.
In December 2014, someone knocked on the door at the Christopheros'.
Andreas said he was going to open the door.
He thought there was probably a courier at the door who was supposed to deliver Christmas presents to the family that day.
Instead, a cruel surprise awaited him.
The man, whom he had never seen in his life, immediately spilled acid on him without warning, saying, "This is for you, my friend."
The pain was indescribable.
The clothes fell apart on me like nothing, and I only felt an incredible pain in my skin," Andreas said.
The family rushed him to the hospital, but there his loved ones learned the terrible news - according to doctors, he had no chance to survive.
A few weeks after the incident, doctors were constantly afraid that their patient would succumb to an infection that threatened to penetrate his wounds.
His injury was very serious.
Ninety percent of the face was hit, which doctors tried to put together using skin from other parts of the patient's body.
A big complication for Christopheros was the loss of eyelids.
It's probably the most torturous thing I've ever experienced.
“You can’t hide from the unexpected light, you can’t close your eyes,” he said.
Today, Christopheros has completed twelve operations, which are far from the last.
Injuries sustained by victims of acid attacks may require hundreds of surgical procedures and years of treatment, according to plastic surgeons.
Even after a difficult and long-term treatment, the victims have scar tissue for the rest of their lives.
"Sometimes people don't recover and they fight deformation and disfigurement all their lives," said Professor Peter Dziewulski, a spokesman for the British Association of Plastic and Aesthetic Surgeons.
The attacker was wrong.
As for the attack, Christopheros is sure that the unknown man must have mistaken him for someone else.
The perpetrator believed he was taking revenge on a man who had sexually abused his loved one.
The police investigated the case and then tracked down the attacker.
The man was initially sentenced to at least eight years in prison.
However, later the verdict changed dramatically to the amazement of the Christopheros family.
"The three judges eventually concluded that the sentence should be lifted because the man is not considered a threat to the public," Christopheros said.
Over the past few years, the number of corrosive attacks has increased significantly.
The Interior Ministry said it plans to set new guidelines for prosecutors on the classification of corrosives.
They should be classified as dangerous weapons.
However, victims of such attacks are not willing to give up.
They demand that the UK government impose more severe and longer prison sentences for people who attack their surroundings with acid or other corrosive substances.
They also call for tighter controls on the sale of hazardous substances, which are often commonly available in different stores as they are different cleaning products.
