Moore's Ford Bridge Massacre: Activists Commemorate Racist Lying
A 1948 Ford Mercury passed by an onlooker in Monroe, Georgia and scrambled towards Moore's Ford Bridge.
However, before a car with four black passengers and a white driver could reach the bridge, a group of white men with guns blocked the way for him.
The leader of the group - a middle-aged man in a striped suit - pulled out a long cigarette and stared at the windshield of the car.
Inside, the passengers trembled with fear.
"We want the n--and Roger!" shouted the man.
“Bring it to me!”
Silence is interrupted by the scream of a young black man being pulled out of the passenger seat.
Fortunately, this scene is merely a reconstruction of the events that took place on July 22.
But when one of the men throws a noose through "Roger's" neck, the audience sighs with excitement.
Since 2005, a group of activists have been returning to Moore's Ford Bridge to reconstruct that fateful night in 1946 when two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcolm and George and Mae Murra Dorsey - were killed by members of the Kukluxklan.
No one has been tried for murder yet.
“It’s a wonder that not a single person has been arrested in all these years - even though we still see them in our community; even though we know their identity,” said Tyrone Brooks, who helps to organize the reconstruction.
“It is a stain on our history and a burden on our souls.”
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia state congressman and lifelong civil rights campaigner.
In his eyes, the reconstruction of the event presents a dramatic call to action, reminding the Monroe community every year that justice has not been done enough.
"We demand a prosecution and closure of the case, we want peace of mind and reconciliation, but justice above all," Brooks said.
“Until then, the process of healing and reconciliation cannot be initiated.”
On July 27, 1946, a medical examiner covers one of the bodies of lynching victims at Moore's Ford.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, up to 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were expected to attend the lynching.
No one has been prosecuted yet.
Despite the fact that the suspects remain at large for decades, civil rights advocates say that both reasons for lynching - politics and sex - were known to all residents of the city.
In April 1946, the Supreme Court granted the citizens of Georgia the right to participate in elections scheduled for the summer for the first time.
According to the FBI, it was during the summer elections that a black farmer named Roger Malcolm allegedly stabbed the white landowner Barnett Hester over his wife.
According to Brooks, it was rumored in town that Hester had been having sex with Malcolm's wife Dorothy and had brought her into a different state.
On July 25, 1946, Loy Harrison, a prominent white-skinned landowner, made a $600 bail against Malcolm.
He was accompanied to prison by Dorothy and cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
On their return from prison, just before entering Moore's Ford Bridge, a group of suspects blocked their way.
"As it turns out, the murders were planned and orchestrated by Harrison," the FBI said.
“It is also clear that there was a secret agreement between state and local law enforcement, who not only participated in the lynching, but also got rid of the evidence and hid the identity of the witnesses.”
Brooks was brief on the matter.
“It was a massacre for the right to vote,” he said.
“The murders had a clear subtext for all black locals: ‘this is how you’ll turn out if you sign up and vote.’
The annual Moore's Ford Bridge reenactment has been organized by Cassandra Greene for nearly a decade.
Her performance is graphic, engaging, and concise, showing deep-seated racism that many would like to consider extinct in modern America.
Watching this reconstruction isn't easy, and it's even more difficult to look away, but Greene says it makes sense.
“No one wants to talk about lynching because we have to face the uncomfortable feelings that are hidden inside each of us,” Greene said.
“There can be no relationship between us if you don’t hear what I’ve been through.”
The main rehearsals of this year's reconstruction began in June, and on the very first day about 30 actors - a dozen whites, the rest blacks - flocked to the room, where Greene introduced them to a very carefully planned performance.
Wade Marbaugh is an assistant director.
For many years, the leader of the Kukluxklan played, but according to him, the role is exhausting.
“I have a bad feeling about this because it goes against who I am,” Marbaugh said.
“I think it’s very important to remember this part of history on a regular basis, because we never want to go back to that time.”
Actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play the role of Roger Malcolm, respectively Barnett Hester, rehearse their roles.
The show begins with a skirmish - Malcolm argues with Hester and blames him for sleeping with his wife.
"Get off my property n--e!"
Rascona can't be done.
There's a fight.
At that moment, everyone (at least every black actor) explodes in laughter.
Greene laughs the most.
“What happened?” asked Rascona.
He's confused.
Was I being too rude?
“No,” Greene replied cheerfully.
"I just don't think white people used to say 'n--r' in that tone."
"Exactly," one of the black actors blurts out.
"You have to put more emphasis on R."
The energy in the room is suddenly better; hostility replaces the feeling of rapprochement.
They all want the performance to be authentic, just to make it worth the four victims of the massacre.
The actors repeat the scene.
Rascona this time emphasizes the correct pronouncing of the word on N.
Now no one's laughing.
The show ends violently and quickly.
The screams, the gunshots... and the silence.
A woman dressed in black stands over the bodies of the actors and sings Billie Holiday's mournful song "Strange Fruit".
With every word there is sadness in the room.
Against the background of all this, about a dozen onlookers wipe sweat and tears from their eyes.
There are almost the same number of blacks and whites in the audience.
One couple came all the way from Ithaca, New York, many bystanders from nearby.
Each endures the local humid climate for nearly eight hours, and Brooks is in a crowd leading to the graves of Malcolm and Dorsey.
Until now, murders could be viewed from a distance, but now, standing in the same place where the lynching took place, the atmosphere is spooky.
With the last words of the song, Greene challenges the crowd to inspect the bodies.
The children kneel at the heads of the victims, watch the fake blood and immobile bodies, and whisper something into their ears.
"They're not dead," the little boy muttered.
It'll be a few minutes, and Greene will thank the audience.
The actors clean the rope and wipe their tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbaugh, the man in the suit who played the leader of the Kukluxklan.
Nick Rascona embraces his two fellow actors and weeps in their arms; eventually he is overwhelmed by emotions.
“It’s okay,” one of the women whispered.
“I know you hate that role.
But you had a reason for it.”
Later that day, the audience sits down with the actors for dinner.
At one table, a young white couple is talking about a performance with a black couple they met today.
Denise Duplinski could barely find words to express her feelings about today's performance.
“It’s hard to listen to those ugly words and look at those hideous acts... done by people who look like you and do it because they look like you,” she said.
“It makes me realize that lynching is still a topical issue,” she added, adding, “it’s just called police skirmishes.”
On the other side of the room, Tyrone Brooks sits in the courtroom, enjoying her dinner while talking about civil rights.
According to his own words, he has already started planning the show for the next year.
“The reconstruction of these events is inspiring because it describes the fear we had to experience, but it is also a moment to reflect,” he said.
“If we don’t learn from it, who knows... it could happen again.
People who do not know and study the history of their country are doomed to repeat it."
