The latest results of tests of asylum seekers in Sweden, who were subjected to a new method assessing their age, show that more than 80 percent of people were surveyed as over 18 years old, but not everyone believes in their accuracy.
The Swedish Forensic Medical Agency began testing the drug earlier this year.
The aim of the method is a more accurate assessment of applicants in the evaluation of asylum applications. The measure was taken after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) was criticized for failing to determine the correct age of some refugees who lied about their age.
To date, the Swedish Migration Agency has submitted 6,880 cases for investigation, and the Forensic Medical Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests, conducted from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
80 percent (2002) were assessed as over 18 years of age, while in another 25 cases the Forensic Medical Agency judged that the respondent was "perhaps over 18 years of age".
In another 423 cases, it was decided that the interviewee was "perhaps under 18".
Tests shall be taken only if the age of the respondent is disputed.
According to Johan Goransson of the Forensic Medical Agency, the results correspond to the previous month.
“Compared to last month, the statistics are very similar,” he told The Local.
A higher number of applicants whose age has been estimated to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that asylum seekers lie about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests, stating that in 442 cases, “the person interviewed was 18 years of age or older.”
The Svenska Dagbladet newspaper investigated 581 published cases and found that in 243 cases, the respondent said he would be 18 years old this year.
There has also been criticism of the medical method of age determination, which includes X-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI scans of knee joints, which are then assessed by dentists and x-rayologists.
One of the skeptics is Claude Marcus from the Karolinska Institute, which, among other things, is concerned with assessing the biological maturity of people to determine the age at which the person went through puberty.
“I had reason to think about this issue and I don’t think these types of measurements to assess age are correct.
In a sense, the assessment of biological age is very uncertain.
If we can't determine age with accuracy, we shouldn't pretend otherwise," he told Metro newspaper.
The forensic medical agency, Agency's Goransson, defended the decision, saying: "In general, the risk of misjudgement of a child as an adult is small.
The highest risk is the fact that the person interviewed is just under 18 years old, which in this case corresponds to 10 percent of all respondents."
