Since the PSG team is funded by a wealthy Qatari family that has grown rich in energy sales, it can afford to bring Neymar into an already star football family.
Clubs can spend huge sums on buying players, but on the other hand, they have to prove legal sources of income, which allows them to cover the overheads of football-related business activities.
The FFP was introduced by Michel Platini after his appointment as UEFA Director in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs that are in debt in pursuit of new reinforcements ultimately cheat and risk bankruptcy if banks or owners refuse to secure them.
In 2011, FFP rules shifted its focus from club debts to monitoring their losses.
This change meant that the business model used by Roman Abramovich with Chelsea in 2003 - to buy a club with potential and spend exorbitant sums for players y build a global brand - suddenly wasn't as profitable.
Under the current three-year trial period, which ends in 2018, clubs can report losses of up to EUR 30 million.
And despite the fact that Platini had to leave his post in 2015, his successor Aleksander Čeferin is determined to defend the ban on excessive spending.
