The first wave of the FFP's highest sanctions hit PSG in 2014, along with Manchester City, which is owned by the Abu Dhabi group.
PSG was fined 60 million euros ($82 million) - which was later reduced to 20 million euros - and ordered to reduce the Champions League squad to 21 players in the 2014-2015 season, instead of 25 players.
UEFA is wary of teams that may try to circumvent financial regulators by increasing their revenues through companies linked to club owners.
Thus, even if the Qatari company sponsors PSG as soon as the funding exceeds the standard market rate, UEFA has the right to prohibit the settlement of the amount.
A similar measure was taken by UEFA in 2014 after it decided that the amount of funding provided by the Qatar Tourism Authority to the PSG team was too high.
Part of Neymar's income in PSG could be paid by the 2022 FIFA World Cup organizing committee in Qatar, according to some reports.
