The Bank of England’s Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) has voted six-to-two to keep the interest rate at 0.25%.
In its annual inflation report, the bank forecast growth to 1.7% in 2017 and 1.6% in 2018, and warned that family budget cuts would continue. The bank expects inflation to rise to 3% in the fall.
At the same time, the bank indicated that there should be growth over the next few years due to inflation caused by Brexit, and also said that rents on capital should increase more than expected in financial markets.
Members of the committee also voted to withdraw part of the mammoth package, which was put into practice a year ago in response to Brexit.
As a result of the above, the Term Financing Plan, which will offer cheap subsidies to banks, should come into effect from next February, although the Bank of England has said that it will now offer 15 billion less than the planned 115 billion euros.
Just before the decision, the bank said: “MPC predicts that gross domestic product (GDP) will stagnate in the short term, along with pressure on real household incomes and consumption burdens.”
On the issue of rates, the bank said it would need to “tighten the belts of monetary policy” to calm inflation, “to a higher degree” than markets expect.
Markets are currently forecasting first growth in the third quarter of next year and further growth in 2020.
However, the bank stressed that any increase would be “slow” and “limited”.
The bank lowered its growth forecast for this year and next, compared to 1.9% and 1.7% in May.
The expected growth of 1.8% in 2018 remained unchanged.
After the publication of the estimates, the pound fell against the dollar and the euro.
The pound fell by 0.5% to $1.31 and by 0.4% to 1.11 euros.
The decision to maintain the status quo came after disappointing growth buried hopes for further growth - GDP stalled to 0.3% in the second quarter compared to 0.2% from the previous three months.
The increase is likely to remain at 0.3% in the third quarter, although it should increase slightly towards the end of the year.
The latest inflation report is a slight consolation for households affected by rising inflation and poor wage increases, the bank said, adding that the situation would worsen before the increase.
The report further states that monetary policy “cannot prevent” income cuts in the coming years, but wages are expected to rise “significantly” towards the end of the three-year forecast.
The economy should also grow due to the strong interest in British goods due to the weak pound, which will compensate for the lower percentage of consumer spending.
The decision came a year after rates were cut to 0.025% last August in response to a shocking vote on the EU referendum, causing the pound to fall.
The bank estimates that a complete unification of prices and the economy will take at least four years.
Prior to the bank’s decision on the latest rates, many had called for an increase in rates, along with rising inflation, which put increasing pressure on households, and three policymakers had called for a 0.5% increase in June.
