NHS to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 patients
Patients will gain access to ‘transformative’ treatment for HIV prevention from September following a Supreme Court decision to fund the NHS drug.
The English National Health Service (NSH) has announced that the pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) pill, which is taken before sex and reduces the risk of infection in high-risk patients by up to 86 percent, will be offered through the health service to approximately 10,000 patients within a three-year trial period.
The NSH agreed to fund a probationary period after an appeals court backed a Supreme Court decision last year saying the NHS had the funds to pay for PrEP despite a statement that the drug should be funded by local authorities.
The decision, which was announced on Thursday, was taken by NHS England from the mouth of CEO Simon Stevens as a 'significant intervention', while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described the decision as a 'decisive moment'.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to begin accepting patients. Other clinics will join in October and by April 2018 there will be full implementation across England.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is an HIV drug given before sex to reduce the risk of HIV disease.
Tests have shown that PrEP significantly reduces the risk of HIV transmission among at-risk patients.
PrEP application before sex means that there are enough specific drugs in the patient's body to prevent infection.
These drugs can be taken every day or at least two hours before sex.
Patients tested include gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and people with HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
Clinics will identify eligible participants who sign consent to participate in the testing, including men, women, transsexuals, and individuals with a partner whose HIV status is not yet controlled by appropriate treatment.
People living and registered with the GP in the UK can also apply at their local sexual health clinic and apply for potential test participation.
The scheme comes to taxpayers at 10 million euros and NHS England has signed a contract this week to distribute medicines following the award of an international public contract.
The trial period is designed to gather clinical evidence and assess the full potential of PrEP, its targeting, use and implementation on a large scale.
Simon Stevens added: “This important intervention should complement and fully burden the ever-expanding and increasingly successful effort to prevent HIV.
It’s another milestone in more than 30 years of trying to stop one of the greatest challenges to human health.”
Deborah Gold, executive director of the National Aids Trust (NAT), said: “We are witnessing a decisive moment in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is given correctly and patients are at risk, it will offer the possibility of transforming the English HIV epidemic.
From September, NSH will offer patients at high risk of HIV infection a powerful new tool that is individually controlled and not subject to the need to persuade a partner, which will lead to an improvement in the quality of many lives.
We are pleased to accept this statement.'
Ian Green, Executive Director of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: “The number one priority must be the rapid deployment of tests across the country; we must make it available to every patient.
We now have the trial drug PrEP, and we are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people at risk of contracting HIV.”
Shadow Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: “The start of the PrEP trial period is a welcome and long-awaited change after months of delays and delays by the government.
The evidence suggests how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the transmission of this life-threatening infection.
Subsequent tests will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
“It is now important that we start testing across the country as soon as possible to protect people who are exposed to HIV and together end the spread of HIV in society.”
