Trump's new chief of staff plans to cut the president's media diet
Many have tried before and always failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can actually do that.
If so, he will be the first.
Politico said the new White House chief of staff plans to restrict the flow of information from President Trump, including news coverage, in the hopes of keeping Trump afloat.
Here's part of a report by reporter Josh Dawsey:
When new White House Chief of Staff John F. Kelly met with staff on his first day in office, he outlined a key problem for Trump’s White House that he intends to correct: incorrect information that gets into the president’s hands.
Kelly told employees that he had to personally approve all information - whether on paper or verbal - because the president could make better decisions based on the right information."
Kelly’s diagnosis actually makes sense, but many of his predecessors have brushed their teeth at Trump’s scrutiny and media presentation.
Trump’s relationship with the media dates back several decades - and now, as he sits in the White House, his habit of watching TV news is even stronger.
“If Trump as a candidate was upset by honest reports, it was fitting to show him that he was being talked about in a positive light by a lot of other media that were easier to convince,” Sam Nunberg, a former campaign adviser, told Politico in February.
Politico’s Tara Palmeri wrote at the time that “the key to keeping Trump’s tweets at bay - at least in the words of six former campaign organizers - is to make sure Trump regularly watches the media who praise him.”
All right.
But the idea that Trump’s tendency to post his views on Twitter has ever been “under control” is ridiculous.
Perhaps these campaign organizers know something that others don’t - that Trump’s tweets would be more outrageous if someone didn’t check them.
The tweets that Trump never sent will most likely never be known.
If his employees managed to keep him at bay at least several times, then their efforts did not go to waste.
But no one has been able to prevent Trump from raising controversial issues on a regular basis.
Part of the problem lies in the fact that in the White House, which is made up of rival factions, people regularly try to strengthen their agenda by slipping Trump materials - which may or may not be reliable - that support their view of the world.
Politico, which covered the issue from all sides, published a report in May on the tendency of advisers to present dubious information to the head of state.
This is an example of such information from the pen of reporter Shane Goldmacher:
Current and former Trump officials say the president often reacts very angry to negative media reports, especially leaks, and seeks to trace their origins.
The situation occurred at the end of February when someone slipped the president a copy of an article from GotNews.com - the website of provocateur Charles C. Johnson - which accused Deputy Chief of Staff Katie Walsh of being the "source of many leaks" from the White House.
Regardless, Johnson was banished from Twitter forever for harassment; or that he did not substantiate his claim with any evidence; or that he had previously published false allegations and later retracted them.
Trump read the article and started asking about Walsh."
Goldmacher added that then-Chief of Staff Reince Priebus and White House Secretary Rob Porter "tried to implement a system to manage and document the information that President Trump receives."
Would that work?
Kelly is now, three months later, trying to push the same strategy.
He may turn out to be a more efficient manager than Priebus, but Trump’s impulsivity doesn’t just fade away and his aides are still competing for power.
These unchanging factors will surely make Kelly's mission harder.
