Michelle Carter Sentenced for Sending Text Messages Inducing Conrad Roy's Suicide
A Massachusetts woman has been sentenced to two years in prison for inciting her boyfriend to commit suicide through text messages and phone calls.
Twenty-year-old Michelle Carter will serve 15 months of a two-year prison sentence and then spend five years on parole.
Carter was convicted in June of inadvertently killing Conrad Roy, who took his own life on July 13, 2014.
Roy’s father told the court on Thursday: “The whole family is devastated.
My son was my best friend.”
Carter was left at liberty until the decision was made.
She was facing up to 20 years in prison, but her lawyers argued that she and Roy were suffering from a mental illness.
Dressed in red pants and a creamy blouse, Carter stood in place of the verdict with tears in her eyes, her hands clasped and her eyes pointed to the ground.
"Her actions killed Conrad Roy," the prosecutor told the judge.
“She ended his life to relieve herself.
She couldn’t take responsibility for herself,” she said.
“She showed no remorse.”
But Carter’s attorney said it was “unfortunate circumstances that he deeply regrets.”
Judge Lawrence Moniz added that “her age or level of maturity or even mental disorder has no significant impact on her actions.”
The plaintiff read a statement from Roy’s mother, Lynn Roy: “There is not a day that goes by that I do not mourn the loss of my son.
I want him to be proud of me - I care for his sisters and together we will endure the immense pain that we will carry with us forever."
Roy's sister, Camdyn Roy, testified that she was "persecuted" by the knowledge that she would never attend her brother's wedding and would never be the aunt of his children.
"The loss of a person I've been seeing since I was born is the pain I'll carry with me for life," she said.
The state of Massachusetts does not have a law in place that would penalize a person assisting the suicide of another person, so this case sets a legal precedent.
Carter was 17 years old when Roy was found poisoned by carbon dioxide in a car seat in 2014.
The case attracted the attention of the entire nation after Carter's text messages were published inciting suicide.
“Hang yourself, jump out of a building or stab yourself, I don’t care,” Carter said in a text message sent just two weeks before his death while Roy was on family vacation.
A few minutes before her suicide, she wrote to him: “You have to do it, Conrad” and “All you have to do is turn on the generator and you will be free and happy.”
Judge Moniz said Carter craved attention through Roy's death and ordered her to refrain from any comments in the press.
The case raised many questions.
One of the people who took Carter's side was Amanda Knox, who was convicted of murdering her British roommate in Italy in 2007. Two years ago, she was acquitted.
Ms. Knox, 30, told the Los Angeles Times: “Michelle Carter deserves understanding and help, not jail.”
