Lavender from Provence is a threat to climate change
Lavender has become a symbol of Provence in the region of southeastern France, but now it is threatened by climate change.
Lavender is declining due to dry climates and harmful insects, causing consternation on the faces of researchers and farmers looking for solutions.
Eric Chaisse, an expert at the agricultural research institute CRIEPPAM in Provence, said: “The cultivation of lavender in Provence is under threat because in the last few years this plant has been exposed to climate change, which brings with it less rainfall in spring and autumn.
This affects the life of the lavender.
Cicadas and locusts carrying the micro-bacteria that thrive in dry climates are also to blame."
There's a lot at stake.
Lavender attracts tourists, and the oil that is produced from it is an important component of perfumes and cosmetics.
Eric Chaisse said: “Instead of long and beautiful flowers, smaller, undeveloped and often weak plants grow.
The amount of oil obtained from these lavenders is, of course, smaller."
A possible solution may be more efficient water distribution and slowing the evaporation of water from the soil, but also spraying lavender with a protective mixture of clay and water and breeding more species resistant to dry weather.
