Among them is co-founder of Riodioce, editor and inspiration for colleagues, Javier Valdez Cardenas.
“The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and working as a journalist,” Valdez wrote in one of his many books on violence linked to the drug trade.
His loss is palpable, though his presence is pervasive - a large photo of Valdez with the inscription "Justice", on which he shows a middle finger, hangs in the front of the building; two journalists - Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez - over 30 years old, have a T-shirt with a photo of Valdez with a smile on his face, glasses on his nose and a Panama cap.
The meeting takes place less than two months after his death; journalists talk about mutual traumas, nightmares, insomnia and paranoia.
Despite the fact that a special federal prosecutor’s office was established in 2010 to deal with journalists’ cases, it has so far sued two suspects, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
Most of the thousands of murders that occur each year are linked to drug trafficking and organized crime, making it extremely rare for journalist killers to go to court.
Journalists from Riodoc insist on reporting on the violence that is happening in Sinaloa; even though they are devastated by grief and the area is currently very treacherous.
Without information about the killers and a vision of justice, the security meeting is pointless, Ibarra says.
