The peace might have angered the sons; the suspected gang members bought all the copies of the newspaper the moment they landed on the shelves.
The second mistake was not to force Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after the seizure of other newspapers in which the same story was published.
Valdez has become a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his death is seen as an important milestone in the fight of Mexican criminals against journalists.
He managed to survive for so long and all his friends and colleagues believed that it would never change.
He was practically a veteran of Noroeste when he decided to sell his $50 stock in 2003 and set up a joint venture with five fellow Riodocs.
In Sinaloa, “it was impossible to do journalism without mentioning the drug trade,” Bojorquez said.
