Dinosaurs used camouflage to avoid enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, however scary.
Researchers have now uncovered the first findings of an amazing rhino-sized creature whose perfectly preserved remains - which experts have dubbed the 'Mona Lisa of the Dinosaurs' - have been found by a Canadian miner.
The remains were preserved to such an extent that experts were able to determine the reddish-brown color of his scaly skin, stating that the dinosaur had a "problem past".
An article in Current Biology called it “the best-preserved armored dinosaur ever found and one of the best species of dinosaur in the world.”
The fossil is a new species of the family Nodosauridae. The dinosaur lived in the Cretaceous period, about 110 to 112 million years ago.
Its perfectly preserved state literally shocked researchers, who described it with the words ‘really remarkable’.
According to National Geographic, the armored herbivore is the best-preserved fossil of its kind to date.
Shawn Funk discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011, while drilling in the Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada.
He came across what looked like a foreign object and decided to explore it more closely.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
The researchers spent the next six years working to uncover an animal from a huge piece of land weighing 1100 kg.
After completing the work, the dinosaur is ready to be discovered.
“You just have to close your eyes a little and you’ll believe they’re asleep,” said lead author Caleb Brown, a naturalist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the animal is on display.
It will certainly go down in history as one of the most beautiful and best-preserved species of dinosaur, the Mona Lisa.
By studying his skin, researchers found that this herbivore - despite being covered in armor and resembling a walking tank - was very likely facing a serious threat from carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armored dinosaur used red and white camouflage to protect against predators and used a camouflage system used by many animals today.
Experts say that this allowed him to better blend in with his surroundings and avoid enemies. The camouflage system indicates that he was a favorite food of larger dinosaurs.
Reports of a 110-million-year-old dinosaur of the family Nodosauridae first appeared in newspapers in May. It is currently available for viewing at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
The researchers named him Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, who and his team spent more than 7,000 hours carefully uncovering the fossil.
Thanks to the amazingly preserved state of the fossil, Dr. Mitchell and an international team of scientists were able to document the patterns and shape of scales and armor throughout the body.
They revealed a method of camouflage commonly used by today's animals in defense - the upper part of the animal was darker than its lower part.
Although this masking effect is common in nature, the researchers’ findings are surprising, as Borealopelta’s size far exceeds that of today’s animals using the same technique.
So it is possible that the dinosaur was such a large number of predators that evolution preferred camouflage to confrontation in survival.
Many modern camouflaged animals - such as deer, zebra, or armadillo - are much smaller and also more vulnerable as prey, suggesting that the nosodaurus had to literally fight for its survival.
“The predation of a huge and heavily armored dinosaur vividly illustrates the dangers posed by predators in the Cretaceous period,” Brown said.
A chemical analysis of the organic components contained in the scales also revealed that dinosaur skin probably had a reddish-brown coloration.
Researchers continue to study the animal and search for more knowledge about its life, including the preserved contents of its stomach, to trace its last meal.
They believe that the dinosaur fell into the river after its death and was taken to the sea, where it sank to the bottom.
In the Alberta area, the climate was the same at the time as in present-day Florida, and rivers and oceans stretched much further inland than they do today.
“This nodosaurus is truly remarkable in that it is completely covered in perfectly preserved scaly skin while being preserved in three dimensions and we can see its original size,” Brown said.
For these reasons, the animal looks practically the same as it did in the Cretaceous period.
You don’t have to use your imagination to reconstruct it; you just have to close your eyes a little and it seems like he’s just sleeping.”
During the Cretaceous period, giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs, roamed the Earth, moving on two legs.
Although the king of all dinosaurs - Tyrannosaurus rex - lived several million years after Borealopelta, this armored dinosaur may have been a favorite prey of his equally fearsome ancestors.
These include Acrocanthosaurus, an 11.5-meter-long monster weighing over 6 tons.
The researchers, whose latest findings were published in the journal Current Biology, believe Borealopelt's body was washed into the sea after being mummified in mud.
Shawn Funk discovered the fossil on March 21, 2011, while drilling at the Suncor Millenium mine near Alberta, Canada.
According to the museum, it is the best-preserved armored dinosaur in the world, including leather and armor, which is also complete from the snout to the hip.
The animal reached an average length of 5 meters and weighed up to 1300 kg.
Two 50 cm thorns protruded from his shoulders.
Researchers believe that this herbivore roamed the territory of present-day Canada until it ended up in a river that washed it into the sea.
His underwater tomb kept the body in perfect condition.
Fossil remains of this species are preserved to such an extent that the armored plates around the skull still cover the remains of the skin.
As Michael Greshko wrote for National Geographic, “The finding of such an individual can be compared to winning the lottery.
The longer I follow him, the more shocking the find seems to me.
Fossil remains of this species are preserved to such an extent that the armored plates around the skull still cover the remains of the skin.
At his side lies his right front leg with his fingers pointing upwards.
I can easily count the scales on his foot.'
How did one activist learn the answer to the question: ‘Whose Streets?’
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell shook her entire body.
The day after she arrived in New York, a native of St. Louis sat on a bed in an Airbnb room and browsed through Facebook posts on her phone.
She came across the contribution of a high school student.
"Police have just shot an 18-year-old boy whose body is still lying on the street," it said.
She was surprised that no one else wrote her this post, so she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
@TheePharoah constantly retweeted her wall posts.
A St. Louis rapper posted on Twitter about the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed 18-year-old who was shot dead by a white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He posted a photo of Brown's body lying limp on the street, from where no one took him even after four hours.
“That’s crazy,” thought Ferrell.
Death was nothing new to her and her family.
She hung up the phone to return to him the evening she watched tweets about people gathering on Canfield Drive.
One of the men claimed to be the victim's father, holding a sign in his hand that read "Ferguson police killed my unarmed son"!
She was watching live news - one of the police officers was standing in front of a group of protesters, holding a leash in his hand and a barking dog on the other end.
In another video, another police officer, she said, was holding a gun pointing at the crowd and shouting, “I’m going to kill you all... the animals.”
“That’s not normal,” Ferrell said.
“This isn’t the kind of murder we’re used to, and we can call it normal.
I felt goosebumps all over my body.
“I was angry and I cried.”
She immediately booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 23:00, she picked up her six-year-old daughter from her father and decided to head to Ferguson in the morning.
The story of what happened to Ferrell and the city of Ferguson over the next three years is described in the new documentary “Whose Streets?”, which will be released on August 11.
It is a story of survival and protest, love and resistance, strength and resilience told from the point of view of people living in a community who take to the streets and demand answers.
On the way to Ferguson, Ferrell introduced a dialogue with her daughter - dressed in a floral jersey and the same floral headband - about a topic they had discussed many times before - "about the experience with blacks".
“Remember how I taught you about how black people had to fight for what they believed in?”
“We’re going to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and that’s not right.”
“There was no way I wasn’t going to take her with me,” Ferrell said later.
“Today’s events are the culmination... of the past.
She had to know and see it with her own eyes and grow up in it.
She needed to develop not only in activism and organizing, but she also needed to know the difference between the different layers of experience with blacks and what we need to do to free ourselves.
Although I am able to provide her with conditions in which she will not experience racism, she is in no way different from another black child-woman.
I feel that if I protected her from this experience, I would only harm her."
Upon arrival in Ferguson, the first stop of the road was South Florissant Road opposite the police department, which became the base of activists awaiting the words of police officer Darren Wilson about his possible involvement in the incident.
Here Ferrell and her daughter met a local businessman who prepared food for others.
Together they prepared food in bags and helped to distribute it to Protestants.
In Ferrell's eyes, a new type of activism was slowly being born.
“My activism turned upside down after August 9,” Ferrell said, adding that while studying at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Assn. Association and sought to introduce health care and food in black communities.
“I had no experience with the organization.
It was natural."
Weeks later, Ferrell met later co-director of the documentary, Sabaah Folayan, during an evening demonstration.
Folayan said he and her cameraman Lucas Alvarado-Farrar wanted to "only document" the ongoing events.
Ferrell thought, “Are you working on a documentary or trying to find a story that could be used?”
This type of skepticism has infiltrated the community through many people, often whites, who wanted to make a living out of pain and determination.
As Folayan explained in an interview, "We've heard that the voices of people who are born and raised in Ferguson are very often overlooked, and we wanted to change that."
Folayan has already teamed up with co-director Damon Davis, who is an acclaimed local artist who deals with the theme of prisoners on death row.
His participation in the project also involved Ferrell and six other locals who were followed by the Whose Streets team in the years following Brown's assassination.
"Nobody speaks for us in this document, but it's our testimony," Davis said.
"That was important to me - how these people will be represented - because in the same way I will be represented."
While the documentary's goal was not to focus on Ferrell's experiences - in an attempt to show that the movement "is not about a savior leader, but about bringing the community together," Folayan said - it turned out that she is the most open to participating in filming.
The documentary "Whose Streets?" thus describes a very personal aspect of Ferrell's life, for example, how she fell in love with her wife.
“I felt naked,” Ferrell said, smiling at the first moment she saw the final version of the documentary.
“But I realized that in order to do this job and humanize black people, I had to open up.”
In addition, Ferrell's story highlights the role of the eccentric black woman in the broader aspect of the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement - who created the #BlackLivesMatter campaign in response to the killing of teenager Trayvon Martin in 2012 on social media - call themselves freaks.
“Black eccentric women in leadership positions are ultimately behind the preservation of the movement,” Ferrell said, “because we are constantly fighting on multiple fronts.
Black eccentric women have to bear the brunt of these events."
Folayan agrees, adding that "the movement is actually supported by black women and a large number of kinky black women."
However, she insists that “this is not just an affirmative issue” and Ferrell is not the main heroine of the documentary because of her views.
“She was the driving force and source of energy,” she said.
It is no coincidence that she was in the front lines, because life at these crossroads in the skin of a black strange woman is dangerous.
You can feel the energy rush in front of the screen.”
Meanwhile, back in Ferguson, television stations' cameras cleared their positions, but heavy racial ties between the community and the police persist.
Ferrell is serving a two-and-a-half-year probation for blocking a highway during demonstrations.
She described the social-political atmosphere in the area she calls home as “The Mess.”
Still, she hasn’t given up on her commitment since she took to the streets of Ferguson three years ago.
“It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We need to love and support each other.
The only thing we can lose is our chains.”
