A Becoming Resemblance: Artist Creates Portraits Using Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the middle of one of the rooms of New York's Fridman Gallery, there are several faces of different skin tones - white, black and brown - hanging from the ceiling on wires. Each of them seems to fall out of the eye of the previous one.
All 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from oral and hair swabs sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent her samples from Fort Leavenworth prison, where a former analyst is serving a 35-year sentence for illegally publishing secret cables on WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on August 2, is titled A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the result of a two-year correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her experience with technology, computer science, and the arts, and Manning, a transgender and pioneering dissident whose sentence was commuted by Obama three days before his departure from the U.S. presidency.
By algorithmic analysis of Manning's DNA and the use of 30 portraits to illustrate what a person with this genotype would look like, Dewey-Hagborg created a sharp, if not intellectual, commentary on the malleability of DNA - as well as the many ways in which DNA can be interpreted - and the inherent determinism of these interpretations, as well as identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward Manning, said she considered herself a woman and was convicted of 20 counts in 2013, including six counts of espionage, computer fraud and theft.
All her photos were kept by prison staff, and only one lower-quality black-and-white photo leaked to the public, with Manning, visibly concerned, sitting in the driver's seat in the platinum-blonde wig she is now associated with.
In 2015, there were still positive reactions to the Dewey-Hagborg project from 2012 Stranger Visions.
As part of this project, Dewey-Hagborg used various forensic objects - such as cigarette butts and chewing gum - to create an image of possible forms of these people.
It was at this time that she received an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They were going to interview Chelsea Manning in prison and they wanted to add a portrait to the story," Dewey-Hagborg said at the opening of the new exhibition.
However, neither visiting nor photographing was allowed, so they turned to Chelsea to ask if she would be interested in a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became friends within two years through correspondence.
They even created a comic strip called Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanung, which presented a vision of what would happen if Chelsea were pardoned and could attend the show in person.
Indeed, a few days after the release of the comic, President Obama asked for Manning’s release, a welcome change after several intolerable years in a Kansas military prison.
Interestingly, the show is taking place at a time when Donald Trump is waging war with people who seek to publish government information and transgender soldiers, while trying to find new ways to fuel resentment with his tweets in the areas he should support.
In response to a question about this particular timing, Dewey-Hagborg said that “everything happens for a reason.”
Under the artist’s statement on one of the gallery walls, Manning calls with her huge signature (the letter “i” in the surname is dotted with the heart) after the end of “self-acting factionalism, which is based on gender, race, sexuality and culture”.
On the opposite side, there are sequences of her mitochondrial DNA - a centipede of the letters C, G and A recorded in pencil.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides, according to Dewey-Hagborg’s sophisticated scientific dictionary), she wanted to illustrate how surprisingly similar, at least biologically, we all are.
“I hope people will take it from this, that our genome doesn’t matter who we are, and that genetic data is subjective and everyone can interpret it in their own way,” said Dewey-Hagborg.
“DNA tells a lot of different stories, this is 30 of them.”
The last specimen of the exhibition, located in a separate room, is the only page from the above-mentioned graphic novel.
It depicts Manning emerging in King Kong fashion from a United States Discipline Barracks prison with a megaphone in her hand.
“As soon as they stop you from speaking, they win,” it says.
“Never let yourself be silenced.”
"It's a direct transcript from one of the letters," the Philadelphia artist said.
"When I think about it, I get goose bumps."
Manning has not yet personally visited the exhibition - as predicted in the comic - but when she does, she will be greeted in the middle of the room with her masks, her own genomic images, lined up like a crowd of Protestants.
This was also the purpose of the exhibition, including a nearly 160 cm tall statue of Maning on which her genetic haplogroups are recorded in pencil.
“In the past, they were placed on the walls, but this time I wanted to make them feel like a crowd,” Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
“I wanted to give the impression of a mass movement that takes the form of Chelsea and frees her.”
Northwestern University professor and Oxford University employee wanted for murder
A nationwide search is underway for a professor at Northwestern University and staff at Oxford University who are being prosecuted for the murder of a man found stabbed to death in a luxury Chicago apartment, police said.
On Monday, an arrest warrant was issued for the first-degree murder of a man named Wyndham Lathem (42) and Andrew Warren (56) for their alleged complicity in the death of Trenton H. James Cornell-Duranleau, according to the Cook County court filing.
Cornell-Duranleau, 26, died of multiple stab wounds.
Chicago police said the body was found on July 27.
Upon arrival at the Grand Plaza Apartments, they found the victim in one of the apartments with several lacerations.
Cornell-Duranleau has been pronounced dead on the scene, and detectives are investigating the case as a homicide, while police are searching for both suspects, authorities said.
Lathem has served as associate professor of microbiology and immunology at Northwestern University since 2007.
Alan K. Cubbage, the university's vice president of public relations, said in an e-mail statement that Lathem is now on administrative leave and was banned from entering the university's school premises.
"The matter is now being investigated by the relevant authorities and the University of the North West is fully cooperating with them," Cubbage said.
Warren is an executive financial administrator at Oxford University.
A spokesperson for the university and Somerville College said in an emailed statement: “We have been contacted by the British police and we are ready to assist the US police as well.”
The statement also said Warren’s colleagues were shocked and wished he had reported to the police.
Anthony Guglielmi, head of public relations for the Chicago Police Department, said he was calling on suspects to surrender to the authorities.
"Police have information about their whereabouts and the search for suspects is intensifying," Guglielmi said.
Guglielmi added that local, regional and national authorities are assisting police in their search for suspects.
According to Guglielmi, police received a call from the manager of the Grand Plaza building, who was alerted to the events that were to occur in apartment No. 1008.
Police described the scene as violent.
Guglielmi said it was unclear if the incident occurred on July 27.
He added that Lathem and Warren had been captured by security cameras.
"We believe Professor Latham knew his victim," Guglielmi said.
The Grand Plaza management issued a statement to all residents: "Police are now working to compile a timeline and profile of the victim and are investigating various motives, including domestic violence."
"In the near future, we will complete the WADA plan" - Deputy Prime Minister Mutko
Russian Deputy Prime Minister Vitaly Mutko said it would not be long before the remaining World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) criteria would be implemented and the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA) re-established.
“Part of the new plan’s criteria has now been finalised and RUSADA has already been granted the right to plan and test in cooperation with the UK Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD).
With this in mind, WADA's plan has been updated," Mutko said on Thursday.
The Vice-President commented on the second part of WADA's compliance plan - which describes the criteria for the renewal of RUSADA - which was recently published on the organization's website.
According to Mutko, the code does not contain anything that Russia should be concerned about.
“Everything has been announced and everything will be implemented.
The results will be available to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and WADA in the near future."
However, one of the criteria mentioned calls for a public announcement of the results of the WADA investigation, which was investigated by Richard McLaren, about the government’s alleged sponsorship of doping by Russian athletes.
Mutko said: “We are conducting an investigation because our anti-doping system has obviously failed.
All measures have been taken.
But there were no state programs in our country, and we cannot admit to anything that never existed."
Mutko’s words were confirmed by Vitaly Smirnov, director of the Russian Independent Public Anti-Doping Commission.
In an interview with Russia's RSport, Smirnov acknowledged the problems of Russian anti-doping officials, but added: "On many occasions we have stated that the report contains controversial positions and regulations.
No one plans to accept the report completely without reservations," Smirnov concluded.
WADA suspected RUSAD of carrying out doping checks within Russia in November 2015 immediately before the doping scandal.
However, the organization allowed the planning and unification of testing under the supervision of international experts and the British Anti-Doping Agency (UKAD) in June this year.
Following a visit to the organization’s Moscow headquarters in July, WADA Director General Olivier Niggli said that RUSADA was “on the right track” to renew.
Police have charged three people, one is a juvenile.
Police have charged three men with setting up a fire to a rare wooden church in Třinec-Guty in Frýdek-Místec.
One accused is a juvenile, all three are Czech nationals.
They face up to 15 years in prison for a crime of general threat.
The Moravian-Silesian Police Director Tomáš Kužel told journalists today.
He said it was an intentional crime.
"It's a very fresh issue and the police are currently working on the motive of the whole issue," Kužel said.
He said police would discuss the possibility of arresting the accused.
Further information cannot be disclosed by the Director.
"I can't say more yet, because the criminal police and investigation service and the prosecutor who oversees the case are really working on it," Kužel said.
The wooden church of the Body of God in Gutech dates from the 16th century.
It was a valuable monument with many original equipment and paintings from the first half of the 16th century.
According to preliminary estimates, the material damage will amount to tens of millions of crowns, but the historical loss is incalculable.
Soon after the fire, the restoration of the church began.
Most of the costs should be covered by insurance, additional costs are prepared to be shared with the Ministry of Culture and the city, a public collection is also being prepared and a contribution from the owner of the monument, i.e. the local parish, is expected.
A similar wooden church of St. Catherine from the 16th century in Ostrava-Hrabová was also destroyed by a fire 15 years ago.
This was caused by an electrical failure.
An exact copy was made in its place.
The state counts on the citizens in the defense of the state.
It will support their training.
Financial support for associations that can be used in the defense of the state, with voluntary shooting training or with a team of training trainers counts on the substantive intention of the Act on the preparedness of citizens for the defense of the state.
The Ministry of Defence, which was given the task by the government, promises to increase the physical fitness of Czechs and their abilities, which could then be used by the state in crisis situations.
This is due to the proposal that the Ministry has prepared.
Should the law be passed in the future, the state would spend hundreds of millions of crowns to support the military.
According to its authors, the basic objective of the proposal is to create an effective system that would help increase the readiness of the inhabitants of the Czech Republic to defend the state, outside the exercise of military duties and on a voluntary basis.
For example, the state would financially or materially support associations of amateurs, shooters or cynologists and would allow to increase the capabilities of their members.
In return, he would get data on people who are willing to come to the aid of the country in times of crisis, and on their abilities or material equipment.
Accredited instructors could also be available to assist associations and other interested parties in their training or education.
It is also planned to organize discussions with veterans or people who have behaved heroically.
One of the possible options assumes that a new office would be created, which would be in charge of the administration and coordination of the project.
The authors of the proposal emphasize that the participation of people should be voluntary and the state would use their abilities only after the declaration of a state of emergency.
"The whole concept must respect the gradual blurring of previously obvious boundaries between different types of threats," the statement said, referring to the dangers of so-called hybrid threats.
Ministerial officials noted that it is therefore necessary to focus on supporting the widest possible set of capabilities, not only military ones.
"The basic objective of the project is to create a very broad base that will allow each citizen to respond competently to situations threatening the sovereignty of the state or the lives, health and property of persons, to protect himself or contribute to the protection of others, and by improper behavior not to make it difficult for the armed forces of the Czech Republic to perform their tasks," the intention states.
The adoption of the law would bring considerable financial demands.
According to the Ministry, their amount will depend on the chosen variant.
For example, the Office envisages financial support for projects to prepare citizens for the defense of the state up to CZK 100 million.
If an administrative and coordination centre were established, its operation could cost around CZK 60 million per year.
More money would be spent on salaries or on building an information system.
The proposal also assumes that the regional military headquarters would have to be expanded, employing 42 additional soldiers.
The ministry said earlier that the law should also help resolve the opposition of some Czech politicians to the introduction of a European Union directive on gun ownership.
Its adoption would allow shooters who will be part of the system to keep some of the weapons prohibited by the directive.
Startups that will help your company not become the next Uber
Amy Errett wanted to measure the level of employee satisfaction of her e-commerce startup, but did not find a corresponding survey.
The answers were often inaccurate, useless, or even misleading.
And despite promising anonymity for the survey, some employees expressed their distrust of the process.
“I was looking for consistency and objectivity,” said Errett, owner of San Francisco-based hair care company Madison Reed, which employs 75 people.
He asked for help from outside.
New HR startups are constantly appearing on the market to help companies with employee satisfaction surveys.
By creating and licensing software with the specific intent of measuring employee responsibilities, startups allow companies to conduct quick voting, target specific teams and demographics, offer total employee anonymity and a hotline for filing complaints, and in some cases, also allow whistleblowers to bypass supervisors and contact directors directly.
“There are tools on the market like Diet and Fitbit that track your health, but where is Fitbit for your company?” said Jim Barnett, co-founder and CEO of Reedwood City-based startup Glint.
Errett said that thanks to Glint, she has gained greater awareness of what her employees think and feel over the past three years.
In addition to quick surveys and voting by specific teams, Glint offers a temperature map of the company and a cursory overview of the groups with the highest number of complaints, as well as an overview of managers with low ratings - allowing the user to work on the remedy.
Companies are starting to realize that it’s necessary to pay attention to the work environment culture - in case they become another Uber - that is reeling from scandals after a former employee posted a post on his blog describing the corporate environment and harassment of employees who dare to speak out.
For startups like Glint, the demand for corporate culture research represents a lucrative business opportunity.
According to the Let’s Talk Payments website, which deals with technical and financial progress, the value of the global control, regulation and compliance industry could exceed $118.8 billion by 2020.
Denver, Colorado-based startup Convert, which helps companies prevent and detect inappropriate behavior, saw a small surge in interest and activity earlier this year, just before the Uber scandals.
Convercent’s nearly 600 clients include Airbnb, Microsoft, and Tesla.
Recently, Uber has also taken over.
Like Glint, Convert allows companies to send customizable “flash” surveys, collect confidential information in real time, and display temperature maps of problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous text hotline that allows employees to report inappropriate behavior.
Where the Director-General is involved, complaints shall be sent directly to the Management Board.
“The court of public opinion has authorized regulators,” said Patrick Quinlan, founder and CEO of the startup Convertent.
If a company is convicted of mishandling its employees or unethical behavior - and regulators fail to intervene - it may face costly consequences as a result of customer boycotts, staff exhaustion, or lawsuits, Quinlan added.
Ruby Tuesday, a restaurant chain that employs more than 25,000 people across 500 locations, has been using Convercent for over a year to raise employee awareness of corporate policies and procedures and provide an easy way to contact corporate executives.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report any problem, he had to trace a phone number or email to the company’s management, officially file a complaint, and hope for a successful resolution.
It was often a daunting and unpleasant experience, said James Vitrano, general counsel for Ruby Tuesday, according to which there had previously been no reliable way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company is using Convertent, rapid detection and resolution of problems that have never before reached office managers is ensured, miles away from real complaint resolution - such as discrimination, harassment, or unfair treatment.
“This comes close to a holistic, overall view of employee experience,” said Vitrano, who heads the Ruby Tuesday group overseeing risk management.
“At the same time, we protect shareholders from litigation by employees.”
Companies stopped taking employee ethics, values and participation lightly in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed after the collapse of Enron over the abuse of employees' ethical rights, Quinlan said.
But it wasn’t until “social media shined a spotlight” that companies began to realize that they couldn’t simply hide their skeletons in a closet in the online world.
“Before people started using technology to monitor ethics, they relied on faith,” Quinlan added.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software in the form of a service for which companies pay regular fees.
It is a business model and an opportunity endorsed by bold capital investors, supported by both startups.
As part of his February campaign, Convercent raised a total of $10 million from firms such as Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, and eventually raised $47 million in capital.
Glint raised $10 million from Bessemer Venture Partners in November and raised $60 million throughout the campaign.
These investments are hardly surprising given the mutual nature of companies, culture and venture capital.
A growing body of research clearly confirms that today’s employees expect more from their workplace than ever before.
And in competitive markets such as Silicon Valley, the main advantage is not high salaries and interesting projects.
Employees want to feel that they are accepted and appreciated and that they are devoting their time to a company that strives for a positive mission.
“If people are happy at their jobs, they perceive that their voice is heard, and that their work is rewarding, they are striving for the company’s success,” said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee benefits at LinkedIn, which uses both Convert and Glint.
Investors make money when a company thrives and a company thrives when its employees are satisfied.
And when an analytical tool appears on the market to ensure employee engagement and commitment to the company, it is no wonder that there are a lot of investors who will support this effort.
According to work culture experts, it is important to have data on employee satisfaction.
But the data itself is useless unless the company takes the necessary steps.
The fact is that once a company asks for feedback from its employees, big changes can occur.
And if the change does not happen quickly - in the worst case ever - it can cause disappointment and indifference among employees.
“Once you ask for 4,000 views, you have to be prepared for 4,000 conversations,” said Russell Raath, director of consulting at Kotter International, who has witnessed many companies rely too heavily on the data itself.
“Because when you don’t get things done, employees start asking themselves, ‘Did they hear me at all?
Are they interested in me?
If not, why should I care?”
Madison Reed, which now conducts monthly employee surveys, is able to solve the problem within a day with Glint, Errett said.
After collecting feedback from employees frustrated by slow decision-making and the quality of communication, Errett was able to reorganize several teams within the company and start training communication to successfully solve the problem.
Ruby Tuesday is gaining a very important perspective on its employees and hopes to achieve high long-term employment in an industry known for frequent layoffs.
“If you don’t strive to create a transparent work environment, employees won’t trust you,” Vitrano added.
“Once you start losing employees, you lose customers.
And with the outflow of customers, the whole company goes bankrupt."
Thursday was the warmest day.
Thursday is the warmest day of the year in the Czech Republic with 38.3 degrees recorded in Strážnice in the Hodonín region.
Tuesday was the warmest day of the year at 37.3 degrees.
This was reported by the Czech Hydrometeorological Institute.
There were not many temperature records on Thursday.
Vedra mainly affected Moravia, in Bohemia it was mostly cloudy.
On Tuesday, records were broken or leveled at 35 of 145 weather stations spanning over 30 years.
On Thursday, only nine long-term measuring stations recorded a record.
For example, in Strážnice today's temperature was the same as the previous record from 2013.
In Lednice in the Břeclav region, today’s 37.4 degrees exceeded the original maximum by four tenths of a degree, and in Pohořelice in the Brno region, the current 37.1 degrees exceeded the record by three tenths.
Both records were set in 2013.
Today, high temperatures have occurred mainly in the south and east of Moravia.
After Strážnice, the greatest heat was in Dyjákovice in the Znojmo region and Brod nad Dyjí in the Břeclav region, where mercury reached 37.8 degrees, but did not break the record.
On the other hand, in western and northwestern Bohemia, according to the CHMI website, today’s highest temperatures were only around 22 degrees Celsius.
"Temperatures began to rise there only now later in the afternoon," meteorologists said.
The current heat in the Czech Republic will gradually subside and more significant rains could come on Sunday.
In most places of Moravia, however, high temperatures will remain on Friday and in the south-east of Moravia on Saturday.
