Making a graphic novel: the story of A Castle in England
The small Scotney Castle recently played a major role in the music video for Squeeze, and Margaret Thatcher found refuge in it during the 1970s and 1980s.
However, Scotney witnessed 700 years of tumultuous history from his cozy spot on the River Bewl in Kent, UK, inspiring the curly-haired Jamie Rhodes of York County - known for his fondness for historical documents - to create a graphic novel.
“The sight of the writing of a man 300 years after death fascinates me,” says Rhodes with a serious face.
“When I hold a letter in my hand, I feel a personal connection.”
The graphic novel A Castle in England documents the lives of families who lived in Scotney Castle from the Middle Ages until the Edwardian period. Each story is illustrated by a different British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
However, this is not Rhodes' first book inspired by archives: he is also the author of Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories (2014), a collection inspired by British Library documents - a project that was very emotional for him.
“I was intrigued by the thumbprint on a letter written by a double agent in the 1970s who worked for the Jacobites,” he said.
"That's his thumbprint!
And letters always smell like smoke, because at that time you had to light a candle to read.
If I smell the letter now, 300 years later, it's like I'm going back in time.
I love the archives!
For someone so fascinated by old papers, the support of the National Trust and Arts Council England and the opportunity to stay in the castle for almost four months is almost like a dream.
Rhodes spent his time exploring the Victorian "new" castle, browsing archives, and studying many treasures and curiosities, such as the head of a hyena on a wall and bottles that had been thrown down a ditch for centuries.
He walked around the grounds and explored the ruins of the old castle, talking to gamekeepers, gardeners and occasionally also artists who worked on illustrations for his book.
“Drinking whiskey and writing.”
The confidential history of Scotney is relatively unknown, as the National Trust did not gain access to the documents until 2006 after the death of the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff were only beginning to penetrate the archives, which Rhodes described in words as "aristocrats of many centuries throwing their hands around with the words 'Put it in the attic'."
Diaries, letters from the time of the British Empire, maps showing the estates: “You may think the land dispute is boring,” Rhodes said, “but I came across one case where two families were fighting over a birch tree.
Stop it, people!"
Some of the stories in the book use the castle as a springboard and delve deeper into English history, including a story called The Labourer, which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the English Rebellion of 1381.
“I found a record of a revolt in the castle from 1380, which was called Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex in the book,” Rhodes said.
“The English rebellion actually started in this area and I thought that the rebellion was a good starting point.
Maybe they’re somehow related.”
Other stories are closely linked to the history of the castle - for example, The Priest, which tells the story of a Jesuit priest, whom the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler about an 18th-century smuggler named Arthur Darrell, who allegedly staged his own funeral when he filled the coffin with stones (which was only discovered a few years after the coffin was unearthed).
Rhodes' favorite family is the Darrells: "I was intrigued by the male generation - men of the time were always in debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Different generations of the Darrell family have dealt with this by marrying rich or old ladies - I imagine they were handsome gentlemen who liked to confuse the heads of heiresses."
With the end of his stay at the castle, Rhodes searches for further adventures.
He recently returned from a two-week stint in the Finnish wilderness, where he soaked up inspiration for his next book about Elämänmäki, a former sanatorium from the early 20th century that was engulfed in nature.
This is a strange place for Scotney.
“I was sad when I left,” he said.
“I was like, ‘Now let’s get the hell back to real life.’
