Red meat, dairy products and chocolate may reduce symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease (IBD)
For your digestive system, red meat and dairy products can be a nightmare.
But a new study suggests the opposite: a diet rich in animal protein and dairy products could help relieve symptoms of inflammatory bowel disease.
An incurable disease that affects up to 1.3 million US residents and 300,000 patients in the UK causes abdominal pain and bloody diarrhea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
Patients are usually reminded not to consume meat and dairy products to relieve symptoms, but researchers at the University of Washington have found that the essential amino acid tryptophan contained in the protein helps build immune cells that support intestinal resistance.
Study leader Dr. Marco Colonna explained that immune cells protect the intestines and ensure the breakdown of harmful microbes from food.
The number of inflammatory cells is balanced by the number of cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissue.
As soon as the scales tilt to the side of inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can occur.
As part of the research, the researchers found the presence of immune cells supporting the body's tolerance in the stomach of mice with a specific bacterium.
This bacterium requires the presence of tryptophan, one of the building blocks of proteins, to make cells.
Professor Colonna said: “We have found a link between one type of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a common part of the gut microbiome and the development of cells that support the body’s tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more these immune cells they had."
He also suggested that if the same turns out to be true for humans, then a combination of L. reuteri and tryptophan-rich diets would help develop a more tolerant and less inflammatory gut environment.
Postdoctoral researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas discovered that one group of test mice had these cells, while the other group of same mice kept separately lacked cells.
She deduced that one group of mice has a different gut microbiome - a community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally reside in the gastrointestinal tract.
The gut of the mice was tested by DNA sorting, and the researchers found six types of bacteria in mice with immune cells that the second group of mice lacked.
Mice that were bred in a sterile environment and lacked an intestinal microbiome - they did not develop this kind of immune cells - were given L. reuteri bacteria - and formed immune cells.
To understand how bacteria affect the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a fluid and then transferred a small amount of fluid - without bacteria - to undeveloped immune cells that were kept in isolation.
Immune cells have evolved into tolerant cells.
After removing the active ingredient from the fluid, it was shown to be a byproduct of tryptophan metabolism known as indolyl-3-acetic acid.
When researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the diet of mice, the amount of these cells increased by 50 percent.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerant cells as mice, and most of us keep L. reuteri bacteria in our gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri bacteria cause cell development in humans in the same way as in mice, but defects in tryptophan-related genes have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan added: “Each of us should probably strive to develop these cells because they control the inflammation of the inner surface of the intestines.
Potentially high levels of tryptophan in the presence of L. reuteri bacteria may increase cell populations."
