White House Props Cost Taxpayers Thousands of Dollars
The White House’s decision to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn to celebrate the U.S. manufacturing industry last month came at $24,000, according to Navy records released by TIME weekly.
The green-white Sikorsky VH-3D helicopter, also called Marine One in the presence of the president on board, was the highlight of the July 17 program at the White House, which was a showcase of U.S. design programs.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence, and several senior White House officials watched the product parade from all 50 states.
A helicopter from Connecticut was on display next to a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a forklift truck from Mississippi.
A White House military officer issued a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, requesting the presence of a helicopter less than 36 hours before the helicopter landed on South Lawn as part of an "extraordinary" event, Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1) records said.
"I wanted to make sure you were aware of such an important event," the HMX-1 commander wrote in an email to his superior, the Navy's deputy commander for aviation, the day before the event began.
The report indicated that the helicopter would arrive at South Lawn at approximately 7:00 a.m. on the occasion of the parade, which is scheduled to begin at 3:00 p.m. and remain in place until the entire site is cleared, which was scheduled between 6:00 p.m. and 9:00 p.m.
The email also stated that if there was a delay on departure from the White House, a replacement crew would be sent for the return flight due to working time regulations.
The original crew remained at the scene that evening, along with a helicopter and a unit of security personnel.
From the records - obtained by the TIME weekly - it was not clear whether the second crew was eventually sent.
The Hatch Act prevents government officials from using government property for political purposes.
Records indicate that HMX-1 is investigating possible violations of this Regulation.
"We were wondering if it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were assured that everything was fine," the commander wrote.
“It sounds like you’ve been blocked,” the deputy commander replied.
This “Made in America” show was designated an official event by the White House, and the Hatch Act would not apply to it.
But even official events have political overtones.
While attending the event, the president advocated health reform, which was going through the Senate, and talked about trying to rein in government regulations.
The use of air vehicles such as Marine One or Air Force One for political purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents use them when they travel.
However, their presence purely for presentational reasons is unusual.
Trump ordered an inspection in February after the presidential plane was flying in the background at his first rally as part of a campaign in Melbourne, Florida. His Twitter account is overwhelmed with complaints about the use of the presidential plane by his predecessors.
"The White House is pleased with the 'Made in America' show, which showcased products from all 50 states made by Americans from American materials," said Lindsay Walters, the White House's deputy press secretary.
HMX-1 crews often practice landings in the Washington area and on South Lawn, rehearsing possible arrivals with the President of the United States to the White House with maximum accuracy.
While Trump attended the G-20 summit in Germany in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 training landings at the White House.
The flight to the Made in America parade was part of the crew's current training, a state official said.
On the same day, the helicopter unit flew as part of “non-presidential support missions” for another eleven hours.
The White House said no additional props were paid from taxpayers' money.
A spokesman for Sikorsky said the company was not involved in any way in the negotiations to display the helicopter on South Lawn.
The HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights, and the exact costs associated with the show are difficult to determine, according to the Navy.
According to the Ministry of Defense, the hourly price for the fiscal year 2017, the reimbursement of DoD expenses for VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
The unit records a time of 30 minutes from Marine Corps Air Facility Quantico base in Virginia and back.
The White House argues that the actual operating costs of the helicopter are well below the stated amount.
“It’s very misleading to report taxpayer costs based on estimates of reimbursements,” Walters said.
“These estimates include personnel, maintenance, and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual cost.”
According to a 2015 RAND study, reimbursements of DoD expenses do not include personnel costs, but include fuel costs, maintenance, and contract costs.
The White House press secretary at the time, Sean Spicer, advocated using the helicopter for the purposes of the show.
“The idea behind the show this week is to showcase products made in the U.S.,” Spicer said.
“I am aware that Sikorsky and the State of Connecticut are very proud of the fact that they contribute to the defense of our state and that they provide jobs to hundreds, if not thousands, of people.
I think, like most Americans, that we are proud of the helicopter and other military facilities that countless American citizens are involved in.
This fact should be remembered.”
It is not clear whether Trump was also looking at a helicopter during his tour of South Lawn. All that can be said for sure is that he sat behind the wheel of one of the fire trucks.
Back in the White House, Trump approached a Sikorsky representative and joked with the media about his own product fleet.
"I know Sikorsky very well," said the president, "I own three myself."
